# Final Benchmark Comparison

| Benchmark | Index Before Load | Load then Index |
|------------|------------------|-----------------|
| Bulk Load | 260 sec | 129 sec |
| Improvement | — | **50% Faster** |
| Index Size | 690 MB | 533 MB |
| Exact Lookup | 17.6 sec | 8.16 sec |

| Benchmark                                          | Scenario 1 (Index Before Load) | Scenario 2 (COPY Before Index)        |              Difference | Observation                                                                                                                   |
| -------------------------------------------------- | -----------------------------: | ------------------------------------: | ----------------------: | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Table Creation                                     |                      39.758 ms |                             42.297 ms |                 +2.5 ms | Negligible difference.                                                                                                        |
| Bulk Load (9,458,171 rows)                         |       **260.594 sec (4m 20s)** |              **129.998 sec (2m 10s)** |        **50.1% Faster** | Loading into a table without indexes is significantly faster because PostgreSQL does not maintain index pages during inserts. |
| Rows Loaded                                        |                      9,458,171 |                             9,458,171 |                    Same | Dataset identical.                                                                                                            |
| Table Size                                         |                        8393 MB |                               8393 MB |                    Same | Data storage unchanged.                                                                                                       |
| Index Size                                         |                         690 MB |                                533 MB |      **157 MB smaller** | Index built after loading produced a more compact B-tree with fewer page splits and lower fragmentation.                      |
| MD5 Index Creation                                 |                Already existed |                            40.634 sec |                     N/A | Creating the index after bulk loading is efficient and recommended for ETL workflows.                                         |
| Exact Lookup (`publication_number='US-4081864-A'`) |                      17.60 sec |                          **8.16 sec** |        **53.6% Faster** | Both use Parallel Sequential Scan; Scenario 2 benefits from better data organization and caching.                             |
| Prefix Search (`LIKE 'US-40818%'`)                 |                   **7.26 sec** |                              7.47 sec | Slightly slower (+2.9%) | Difference is negligible; no index exists on `publication_number`, so both perform full table scans.                          |
| Title Search (`ILIKE '%helmet%'`)                  |                   **7.39 sec** |                              8.20 sec |                  +10.9% | Similar execution plan (Parallel Seq Scan); runtime variation is likely due to cache or system state.                         |
| Abstract Search (`ILIKE '%water%'`)                |                     Not Tested |                         **21.70 sec** |                     N/A | Large result set (361,777 rows) requires scanning the entire table.                                                           |
| Query Plan                                         |              Parallel Seq Scan |                     Parallel Seq Scan |                    Same | No search-specific indexes available in either scenario.                                                                      |
| Parallel Workers                                   |                              2 |                                     2 |                    Same | Parallel execution unchanged.                                                                                                 |
| Access Method                                      |                           Heap |                                  Heap |                    Same | Same storage engine.                                                                                                          |


---

# Conclusions

- UNLOGGED tables significantly reduce bulk loading time.
- Loading data before creating indexes improves ETL performance by approximately 50%.
- Hash partitioning helps equality lookups through partition pruning.
- Prefix and text searches still require sequential scans without dedicated indexes.
- Building indexes after bulk loading creates more compact B-tree indexes and reduces fragmentation.

